      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was reading a manual for a cessna 172 and saw stuff about the pitot tube. can u explain how it actually works to measure airspeed? and why is it such a big deal if it gets blocked up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the pitot tube, a trusty little device that measures the airspeed of your Cessna 172, much like a clever little gnome measuring the speed of a river with a twig. It works by comparing the pressure of the air flowing into it with the static air pressure outside. Imagine a tiny, invisible wind tunnel that gobbles up the air and spits out a reading, much like a goblin gobbling up a snack and then giving you a number. \n\nNow, if that pitot tube gets blocked up, it's like a goblin blocking the entrance to a treasure cave. The air can't flow through properly, and the readings become all wonky. It's a big deal because without accurate airspeed, it's like trying to navigate a forest without a map – you could end up in a thicket or, worse, crash into a tree. So, keep that pitot tube clear, or you'll be left with nothing but goblin whispers and a very confused pilot.",
