    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see you're looking for the nitty-gritty, the real goblin gold of the pitot-static system. Alright, let's dive into the physics, shall we? The pitot tube measures the dynamic pressure, which is the pressure of the air moving towards it. This dynamic pressure is the difference between the total pressure (the sum of static and dynamic pressures) and the static pressure (the pressure of the air not moving towards the pitot tube).\n\nThe formula to calculate airspeed (V) from the dynamic pressure (q) is derived from Bernoulli's equation and is given by:\n\nV = sqrt((2 * q) / ρ)\n\nwhere ρ (rho) is the air density. The dynamic pressure (q) is calculated by subtracting the static pressure (P_static) from the total pressure (P_total) measured by the pitot tube:\n\nq = P_total - P_static\n\nSo, the airspeed is calculated by taking the square root of twice the dynamic pressure divided by the air density. This gives you the velocity of the aircraft relative to the air around it.\n\nNow, if the pitot tube gets blocked, the total pressure (P_total) can't be measured correctly, and the dynamic",
